{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17518123","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17518123"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T14:00:48+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T14:00:48+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12882"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"12882","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/12882"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.11,0.4,0.27,0,0.22]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"5324"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"54122"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"5324","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/5324"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12882"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"39594"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"14"},{"type":"tags","id":"37"},{"type":"tags","id":"39"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"1061"},{"type":"tags","id":"3479"},{"type":"tags","id":"4658"},{"type":"tags","id":"4815"},{"type":"tags","id":"4923"},{"type":"tags","id":"4983"},{"type":"tags","id":"9051"},{"type":"tags","id":"9663"},{"type":"tags","id":"11643"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"9050"},{"type":"contributions","id":"9760"},{"type":"contributions","id":"15500"},{"type":"contributions","id":"35080"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44385"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44829"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"54122","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/54122"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 42-year-old man presents to the Emergency Department with a three-day history of low-grade fevers that worsened today. He is now complaining of joint pain, chills, and rigors.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHe has a medical history of splenectomy following a traumatic motor vehicle accident, HIV infection (viral load undetectable), and hereditary complement deficiency. His regular medications include amoxicillin and Biktarvy (bictegravir/emtricitabine/tenofovir alafenamide). He engages in unprotected anal and oral sex with multiple sexual partners.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears unwell. His pulse rate is 110/min, blood pressure 130/80 mmHg, respiratory rate 22/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 39.0\u00b0C. He has multiple non-tender pustules on his trunk. His wrist and ankle joints are swollen and tender to palpation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EBlood cultures return positive for gram-negative diplococci.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely reason for this patient developing this particular presentation of his infection?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["HIV infection","Unprotected sex with multiple partners","Previous splenectomy","Age","Complement deficiency"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient\u0027s presentation is consistent with disseminated gonococcal infection, caused by \u003Cem\u003ENeisseria gonorrhoeae (N. gonorrhoeae)\u003C/em\u003E. The blood culture positive for gram-negative diplococci, along with the clinical picture strongly suggest this diagnosis. Disseminated gonococcal infection frequently presents with arthritis-dermatitis syndrome, a triad of tenosynovitis, dermatitis that is pustular, and polyarthralgia. The question specifically asks about the reason for dissemination of the infection in this patient.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EComplement deficiency\u003C/strong\u003E is the most likely reason for this patient developing disseminated gonococcal infection. Complement-mediated killing via opsonisation and the membrane attack complex plays a major role in controlling \u003Cem\u003EN. gonorrhoeae\u003C/em\u003E, particularly the terminal pathway (C5-C9). A complement deficiency significantly impairs the host\u0027s ability to control gonococcal infections and predisposes to the risk of overwhelming disseminated infection. Up to 50% of patients with terminal complement deficiency may develop disseminated gonococcal infections during their lifetime.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHIV infection\u003C/strong\u003E can increase the risk of opportunistic infections and severe septicaemia. However, this patient has well-controlled HIV with an undetectable viral load, meaning his immunosuppression is not primarily due to HIV, making it unlikely to be the primary factor causing his current condition. While there is an epidemiological association between HIV and \u003Cem\u003EN. gonorrhoeae\u003C/em\u003E, HIV itself does not typically lead to disseminated gonococcal infection in the absence of severe immunosuppression.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHaving \u003Cstrong\u003Eunprotected sex with multiple partners\u003C/strong\u003E increases the risk of acquiring \u003Cem\u003EN. gonorrhoeae\u003C/em\u003E and other sexually transmitted infections. However, this factor alone does not explain why the infection has become disseminated.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Esplenectomy\u003C/strong\u003E increases the risk of infections, particularly by encapsulated organisms such as \u003Cem\u003ENeisseria meningitidis\u003C/em\u003E, \u003Cem\u003EStreptococcus pneumoniae\u003C/em\u003E, and \u003Cem\u003EHaemophilus influenzae\u003C/em\u003E. Unlike \u003Cem\u003ENeisseria meningitidis\u003C/em\u003E, \u003Cem\u003EN. gonorrhoeae\u003C/em\u003E is not encapsulated and a previous splenectomy is not typically associated with an increased risk of disseminated gonococcal infection.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAge\u003C/strong\u003E is not a significant risk factor for disseminated gonococcal infection. While these infections are more commonly seen in younger patients (\u0026lt;40 years), likely due to lifestyle factors, age itself does not explain the dissemination of the infection.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn summary, while several factors contribute to this patient\u0027s risk of acquiring gonorrhoea, his complement deficiency is the most likely reason for the development of disseminated infection.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Disseminated gonococcal infection can present with a triad of polyarthralgia, dermatitis and tenosynovitis - \u0027arthritis-dermatitis\u0027 syndrome.","Terminal complement deficiency is a significant risk factor for recurrent disseminated gonococcal infection."],"references":["Tahir F, Ahmed J, Malik F. Post-splenectomy Sepsis: A Review of the Literature. Cureus. 2020 Feb 6;12(2):e6898. doi: 10.7759/cureus.6898. PMID: 32195065; PMCID: PMC7059871.","Disseminated gonococcal infection. Klausner JD. In T.W. Post, P. Rutgeerts, \u0026 S. Grover (Eds.), UptoDate. Available from https://www.uptodate.com/contents/disseminated-gonococcal-infection#H3"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"39594"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12882"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"39594","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/39594"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-09-30T14:38:31+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-05-02T00:29:37+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"5324"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"54122"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"14","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/14"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udda0","name":"Infectious Diseases","synonyms":["ID"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2021-05-21T